John,<br>
     I'll second Tom's post.  However, I have some fish of my own to fry.                                                                                                          Without the British Navy, the Monroe Doctrine wouldn't have been worth the paper it was printed on.  We didn't have the military power to enforce it until the end of the Civil War, after which France abandoned Maximillian in Mexico.  As for George III, he was the first Hanoverian monarch to receive an English education.  Please, Germany has enough on its conscience without an extra undeserved load.  The modern form of &quot;Divine Right of Kings&quot; came out of France, specifically the regime of Louis XIV, who said he was the state.  The very real grievances of the American colonists notwithstanding, Jefferson uses exaggerated broad brush tactics on George in the Declaration of Independence.                                                                                                                            Also, before you reiterate that free speech is muzzled these days; please note that you are evidently alive, under no involuntary servitude and unincarcerated.  In all probability, you're not under any surveillance either.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


